 for bestpractices and # User Profile

## Overview
Build a comprehensive User Profile experience within LuxeFlow CRM that empowers users to manage their personal profile (avatar, contact info), security (password, 2FA), notification preferences, and API token access, while enforcing robust authentication, authorization, and role-based access across Admin, Agent, Ops, and Finance. This feature intersects with User Management (admin capabilities to create/edit users, assign roles, manage SSO/SAML, and deactivate accounts) and integrates with the broader Auth & Roles system and session management. The result should be a polished, premium, enterprise-ready UX that feels luxurious, secure, and efficient.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The User Profile page is the personal hub for a logged-in user to control their avatar, contact details, password, multi-factor authentication (2FA), notification preferences, and API token management. It also surfaces recent activity and active sessions to help users monitor account activity.

Goals:
- Allow users to securely update their personal information and security settings.
- Enable self-serve 2FA enrollment/remediation and 2FA backup options.
- Provide granular notification preferences with per-channel controls (email, SMS, in-app).
- Manage personal API tokens (creation, revocation, scopes) for power users.
- Display recent activity and active sessions with safe logout capabilities.
- Enforce role-based access controls at the UI level, ensuring Admins can manage user accounts and SSO/SAML settings via User Management page, while other roles have restricted access in this scope.

Connected features and UI elements:
- Profile Info Form: avatar upload/selection, name, email, phone, locale, time zone.
- Security: password change flow, 2FA setup (TOTP/app-based, SMS fallback if enabled), backup codes, re-issuance of codes.
- Notification Preferences: per-channel toggles, per-event granularity, default channels, and sample previews.
- API Token Management: list tokens, create new token with scope/selectable permissions, revoke tokens, audit trails.
- Activity & Sessions: recent logins, IPs, device names, last active timestamp; ability to logout other sessions.
- SSO/SAML status awareness (for Admins/Ops): status indicators, integration links, and quick access to manage in User Management where applicable.
- API Integrations: No external APIs required for this MVP, but the page is designed to work with the platform’s Auth, Sessions, and Roles services.

UI guidance:
- A refined, luxury aesthetic aligned with LuxeFlow design system.
- Clear sectioning with generous whitespace, soft borders, and elevated cards.
- Primary actions highlighted with olive green accent; secondary actions are muted.
- Responsive design: fully usable on desktop and mobile with a collapsible mobile navigation pattern.

Integrated platforms and data flow:
- The page reads and writes to the platform’s user profile store and authentication/session services.
- It consumes the current user’s data from the authentication layer and supplements with profile fields from the user SQL/NoSQL store.
- For Admins editing other users (via User Management), it interacts with backend APIs for user CRUD, role assignment, SSO/SAML configuration, and deactivation.

## Components to Build
- ProfileHeaderCard
  - Avatar upload, display, and avatar cropping support.
  - Quick status indicators (2FA enabled, last login).
- ProfileForm
  - Name, email, phone, locale, time zone fields.
  - Real-time validation with accessible error messaging.
- SecurityPanel
  - PasswordChangePanel: current password, new password, confirm password with strength indicator.
  - TwoFactorPanel: enable/disable, QR code or setup instructions, backup codes management, recovery options.
- NotificationPreferencesPanel
  - Per-channel (Email, SMS, In-App) toggles.
  - Per-event toggles (Booking updates, Payments, System alerts, Personal messages).
  - Preview area showing a sample notification layout.
- ApiTokensPanel
  - Token list with masked values, creation modal with scope selection, expiration settings, and revocation actions.
- ActivitySessionsPanel
  - List of recent sessions with device, location, timestamp, and logout controls.
- SSO_SAMLPanel (Admin/Ops only)
  - Overview status, connectors, and quick link to User Management for detailed config.
- ConnectedSettingsPanel
  - Links and toggles for linked accounts, SSO, and SAML associations (read-only for non-admins).
- ConfirmationDialog
  - Reusable modal for destructive actions (token revoke, session termination, account deactivation by Admins).
- Toasts/Snackbars
  - Non-intrusive feedback for success/failure with accessible ARIA live regions.

Technical details:
- Each panel should be a self-contained React component (or framework equivalent) with clear props and state hooks.
- Ensure all forms perform client-side validation with accessibility in mind (aria-invalid, aria-live, role="alert" for errors).

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks/Tech: React (with TypeScript), Zustand or Redux for state where appropriate, and a UI library aligned with the LuxeFlow design system (or fully custom components as needed).
- State management: Use useState and useEffect with proper defaults; arrays initialized as [] and objects as {} where applicable.
- Runtime safety:
  - Guard all array operations: (items ?? []).map(...), Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize state with correct types: useState<UserProfile[]>([]) for arrays, useState<Token[]>([]) for tokens, etc.
  - When handling API responses, validate shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
  - Use optional chaining for nested data: user?.profile?.avatarUrl, settings?.notifications?.email, etc.
- Accessibility: all forms include proper labels, error messages, focus management, and keyboard navigation.
- Avatar management: client-side image cropping/resizing with constraints (min/max dimensions) and upload to backend with a safe, resumable flow.
- 2FA setup: integrate with TOTP; present QR code; provide backup codes; handle enabling/disabling securely.
- Token management: create/revoke tokens with scoped permissions; tokens should not be exposed in plain text beyond creation time.
- Session management: show active sessions with ability to log out across devices; ensure logout prompts confirm intent.
- Validation rules:
  - Email format validation with debounce where appropriate.
  - Password validation rules (min length, complexity) and strength meter.
  - Phone number validation with optional international format.
  - Time zone and locale validation against supported lists.
- Data fetching and caching:
  - Use data ?? [] safety for all list results.
  - Use loading states and skeletons for lengthy fetches.
- Error handling:
  - Centralized error handling for API calls; display user-friendly messages.
  - Retry mechanisms for transient failures where appropriate.

### Backend
- APIs (assuming REST or GraphQL as per project standards):
  - GET /api/users/me: fetch current user profile.
  - PUT /api/users/me: update personal profile (name, email, phone, avatarUrl, locale, timeZone).
  - POST /api/users/me/password: change password.
  - POST /api/users/me/2fa/setup: initiate 2FA setup; return QR code data or provisioning URL.
  - POST /api/users/me/2fa/verify: verify 2FA token during setup.
  - POST /api/users/me/2fa/disable: disable 2FA.
  - GET /api/users/me/notifications: fetch notification preferences.
  - PUT /api/users/me/notifications: update notification preferences.
  - GET /api/users/me/tokens: list API tokens.
  - POST /api/users/me/tokens: create a new API token with scopes.
  - DELETE /api/users/me/tokens/{tokenId}: revoke a token.
  - GET /api/users/me/sessions: fetch recent sessions.
  - POST /api/users/me/sessions/logoutAll: terminate all other sessions.
  - Admin-only: GET/POST/PUT/DELETE /api/users/{id} for user management (roles, SSO/SAML, permissions, deactivate).
  - Admin/Ops: endpoints for SSO/SAML configuration per user or org as applicable.
- Database tables (conceptual entities):
  - users (id, name, email, phone, avatar_url, locale, time_zone, password_hash, is_2fa_enabled, created_at, updated_at, active)
  - user_roles (user_id, role_id)
  - roles (id, name, permissions_json)
  - user_sso (user_id, sso_provider, sso_id, is_active, last_used)
  - user_notifications (user_id, channel, events_json)
  - api_tokens (id, user_id, token_hash, name, scopes_json, created_at, expires_at, revoked)
  - user_sessions (id, user_id, device_name, ip_address, last_used_at, is_current)
  - audit_logs (id, user_id, action, target_id, timestamp, details)

- Security:
  - Enforce RBAC: Admins can manage users; Agents/Ops/Finance have restricted access per feature.
  - Password hashing with bcrypt/argon2 as per standards.
  - 2FA secret storage securely (encrypted at rest).
  - Token storage with one-way hashing; never expose token values in API responses.
  - Input validation on server side mirroring frontend rules.
  - Rate limiting on sensitive endpoints (password reset, 2FA changes, token creation).

### Integration
- Authentication & Roles:
  - Integrate with existing Auth service for current user context, roles, and permissions.
  - Enforce UI-level role guards in the Profile page (e.g., show SSO/SAML management only to Admins/Ops).
- Data flow:
  - Profile page reads from /api/users/me and complementary endpoints for dependent data (tokens, notifications, sessions).
  - Admin User Management page interacts with broader endpoints for user CRUD and SSO/SAML management.
- UI State Synchronization:
  - After updates (profile, password, 2FA, notifications, tokens), optimistically update UI with immediate feedback and revert on error.
  - Centralized error boundary and toast notifications for success/failure.

## User Experience Flow
1) User logs in with their credentials and is redirected to their User Profile page.
2) ProfileHeaderCard displays avatar with option to upload/change; shows 2FA status and last login.
3) User opens ProfileForm to edit name, email, phone, locale, and time zone; saves with validation; success toast shown.
4) User navigates to SecurityPanel:
   - If 2FA is disabled, they can set up 2FA (scan QR, enter code, verify); upon success, 2FA status flips to enabled.
   - If 2FA is enabled, they can disable or rotate 2FA, and view/generate backup codes.
5) User navigates to NotificationPreferencesPanel:
   - Adjust per-channel and per-event settings; sample preview updates live.
6) User navigates to ApiTokensPanel:
   - View tokens, create new token with chosen scopes, give token a friendly name, and copy value once created; revoke tokens as needed.
7) User navigates to ActivitySessionsPanel:
   - Review recent sessions; sign out from other devices with confirmation.
8) Admin/Ops flow (via User Management):
   - Open a separate Admin page for a user; update roles (Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance), manage SSO/SAML connections, set granular permissions, and deactivate accounts.
9) All actions provide accessible confirmations and rollbacks if errors occur.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: [Schema details]
- User
  - id: string
  - name: string
  - email: string
  - phone?: string
  - avatar_url?: string
  - locale: string
  - time_zone: string
  - password_hash: string
  - is_2fa_enabled: boolean
  - last_login_at?: string
  - created_at: string
  - updated_at: string
  - active: boolean
- UserProfile (embedded or separate as needed)
  - user_id: string
  - additional_profile_fields...
- Token
  - id: string
  - user_id: string
  - name: string
  - token_hash: string
  - scopes: string[] (or JSON)
  - created_at: string
  - expires_at?: string
  - revoked: boolean
- Session
  - id: string
  - user_id: string
  - device_name: string
  - ip_address: string
  - last_used_at: string
  - is_current: boolean
- NotificationSettings
  - user_id: string
  - channel: string (email|sms|in_app)
  - events: string[]  // e.g., booking_created, payment_due
- 2FA
  - user_id: string
  - secret_encrypted: string
  - enabled: boolean
  - recovery_codes: string[] // encrypted or tokenized
- Role
  - id: string
  - name: string  // Admin, Agent, Ops, Finance
  - permissions: string[] // permission keys
- UserRole
  - user_id: string
  - role_id: string

API Endpoints: [Routes and methods]
- GET /api/users/me
- PUT /api/users/me
- POST /api/users/me/password
- POST /api/users/me/2fa/setup
- POST /api/users/me/2fa/verify
- POST /api/users/me/2fa/disable
- GET /api/users/me/notifications
- PUT /api/users/me/notifications
- GET /api/users/me/tokens
- POST /api/users/me/tokens
- DELETE /api/users/me/tokens/{tokenId}
- GET /api/users/me/sessions
- POST /api/users/me/sessions/logoutAll
- GET /api/users/{id}
- PUT /api/users/{id}
- DELETE /api/users/{id}
- POST /api/users/{id}/deactivate
- POST /api/users/{id}/sso/connect
- GET /api/organizations/{orgId}/sso/config
- PUT /api/organizations/{orgId}/sso/config
- ... (admin/ops scoped endpoints as defined in your RBAC policy)

Security: [Authentication, authorization requirements]
- Use existing authentication (JWT/OAuth session) with role-based access control (RBAC).
- Admins can manage users; only Admins/Ops can modify SSO/SAML connections; non-admins see read-only sections as applicable.
- Ensure all sensitive operations require current password re-entry or 2FA verification when applicable.
- All API responses must be sanitized; never leak secrets or token values post-creation beyond the initial token string returned at creation time.
- Data at rest encrypted for sensitive fields (2FA secrets, recovery codes, tokens).
- CSRF protection for state-changing endpoints if using cookies; use anti-forgery tokens where required by framework.

Validation: [Input validation rules]
- Name: 2-64 characters; letters, spaces, hyphens; disallow leading/trailing spaces.
- Email: RFC5322-compliant validation; unique constraint at backend.
- Phone: E.164 format optional; validate length and allowed characters.
- Avatar: file type (png/jpg/jpeg), max size (e.g., 2-5MB), resize to standard dimensions.
- Password: minimum 12 chars, at least one uppercase, one lowercase, one number, one special char; disallow common compromises; confirm password.
- 2FA: verify TOTP code against shared secret; enforce after setup completion.
- Tokens: token name length, scopes non-empty; expiration within allowable range.
- Notifications: ensure channels are valid and events mapped to known events.
- Sessions: ensure logout requests are scoped to current user or admin-initiated for other sessions with proper audit.

Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] User can update profile fields (name, email, phone, locale, time zone) with real-time validation and success toast; data persists and reflects in UI.
- [ ] 2FA setup flow completes: QR provisioning, verification code accepted, 2FA enabled; backup codes generated and accessible securely.
- [ ] Notification preferences save per-channel and per-event with immediate UI reflection and correct defaults.
- [ ] API tokens: create, copy once, revoke, and list tokens; tokens are not retrievable in plain form after creation; revocation removes access.
- [ ] Sessions: display all recent sessions; user can logout from other devices; current session remains active.
- [ ] Admin/User Management integration: Admins can view/edit user roles, manage SSO/SAML, set permissions, and deactivate accounts via the Admin page; changes are persisted and reflected in listing.
- [ ] Security: All endpoints protected; unauthorized attempts are denied with proper HTTP status codes; sensitive fields are never exposed.

UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- See Visual Style section below for color, typography, spacing, and interactive behaviors.
- Use Card-based layouts with subtle shadows, rounded corners, and light dividers.
- Ensure top navigation remains accessible with sticky header behavior and focus states.
- Ensure responsive behavior: mobile nav, stacked sections, touch-friendly controls.
- Use olive green accent for primary call-to-action buttons and key toggles.
- Use serif headings (Playfair Display/Georgia) and sans-serif body text (Lato/Helvetica Neue).
- Maintain generous whitespace, clear hierarchy, and restrained micro-interactions.

Visual Style

Color Palette:
- Primary: #FFFFFF
- Accent: #8A9A5B
- Neutrals: #F6F6F6, #EEEEEE
- Text: #222222, #888888
- Supporting: #C6AB62
- Imagery: High-resolution warm-toned photography

Typography & Layout:
- Headings: Playfair Display or Georgia
- Body: Lato or Helvetica Neue
- Hierarchy: Large headlines, subtler subheads, readable body text
- Spacing: Generous padding; clear separation between sections
- Alignment: Left-aligned content; center-aligned headers for key callouts
- Treatments: Uppercase for section labels; italic for quotes/testimonials (if used)

Key Design Elements
- Card Design: White cards, soft shadows, 4-8px radius
- Dividers: Thin light gray lines
- Hover States: Subtle shadow lift; accent border on selection
- Visual Hierarchy: Top image or heading, then content sections

Navigation
- Top Nav: Centered/left-aligned logo; minimal menu with hover underline
- Sticky Header: Visible on scroll with fade effect
- Active States: Accent underline
- Responsive: Mobile nav with hamburger menu

Data Visualization
- Not core to this page; use minimalist indicators if needed

Interactive Elements
- Buttons: Olive green, white text; bold padding; hover shadow
- Forms: White inputs with thin borders; clear focus state
- Dropdowns/Selects: Simple, accessible
- Micro-interactions: Smooth transitions, restrained feedback

Design Philosophy
- Luxury, modern, minimalistic
- Clarity, generous whitespace, calm professionalism
- Premium feel with efficiency for power users

Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety
- Supabase/query results: data ?? [] (if using Supabase)
- Array methods guarded: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
- React useState: useState<T[]>([]) for arrays; useState<{...} | null>(null) only where appropriate for single objects
- API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Optional chaining: obj?.property?.nested
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

